SIMPLE: wrench
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wrench
<hw>Wrench</hw> <pr>(r⟦ecr⟧nch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wrench</ets> deceit, AS. <ets>wrenc</ets> deceit, a twisting; akin
to G. <ets>rank</ets> intrigue, crookedness, <ets>renken</ets> to bend,
twist, and E. <ets>wring</ets>. ⟦root⟧144. See <er>Wring</er>, and cf.
<er>Ranch</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Trick; deceit; fraud; stratagem.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His wily <qex>wrenches</qex> thou ne mayst not flee.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A violent twist, or a pull with twisting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He wringeth them such a <qex>wrench</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Skelton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The injurious effect upon biographic literature of all such
<qex>wrenches</qex> to the truth, is diffused everywhere.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sprain; an injury by twisting, as in a
joint.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Means; contrivance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An instrument, often a simple bar or lever with jaws
or an angular orifice either at the end or between the ends, for
exerting a twisting strain, as in turning bolts, nuts, screw taps, etc.;
a screw key. Many wrenches have adjustable jaws for grasping nuts, etc.,
of different sizes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The system made up of a force and
a couple of forces in a plane perpendicular to that force. Any number of
forces acting at any points upon a rigid body may be compounded so as to
be equivalent to a wrench.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Carriage wrench</b></col>, <cd>a wrench adapted for
removing or tightening the nuts that confine the wheels on the axles, or
for turning the other nuts or bolts of a carriage or wagon.</cd> --
<col><b>Monkey wrench</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Monkey</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Wrench hammer</b></col>, <cd>a wrench with the end shaped so as
to admit of being used as a hammer.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrench</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wrench
<hw>Wrench</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wrenched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wrenching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>wrenchen</ets>, AS.
<ets>wrencan</ets> to deceive, properly, to twist, from <ets>wrenc</ets>
guile, deceit, a twisting. <?/<?/<?/<?/. See <er>Wrench</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To pull with a twist; to wrest, twist, or force by
violence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Wrench</qex> his sword from him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Forthwith this frame of mine was <qex>wrenched</qex>⟦br⟧
With a woeful agony.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strain; to sprain; hence, to distort; to
pervert.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You <qex>wrenched</qex> your foot against a stone.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrest</ent>⟦br⟧
